WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.297
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.652 --> 00:00:08.230
KAREN MAY: So thank you
so much for joining us.

00:00:08.230 --> 00:00:10.820
Kelsey is here today, not
only the author of this book,

00:00:10.820 --> 00:00:14.770
but the founder of Help Each
Other Out, her organization.

00:00:14.770 --> 00:00:20.230
And she works at UC Berkeley
as well as Cal State University

00:00:20.230 --> 00:00:22.870
and has been featured on NPR,
and "The Washington Post,"

00:00:22.870 --> 00:00:24.970
and a number of
other media outlets.

00:00:24.970 --> 00:00:26.470
And we're lucky
to have her today,

00:00:26.470 --> 00:00:28.690
and I appreciate you
coming to join us.

00:00:28.690 --> 00:00:30.820
So we're going to hear
a bit from Kelsey,

00:00:30.820 --> 00:00:33.850
and then we'll have some
time for Q&amp;A. I have a couple

00:00:33.850 --> 00:00:35.710
questions teed up,
but primarily, we'll

00:00:35.710 --> 00:00:37.730
make space for your questions.

00:00:37.730 --> 00:00:39.610
There is a Dory in
the calendar invite.

00:00:39.610 --> 00:00:41.080
So if you're
watching live stream

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:43.780
and you'd like to put a question
in, or if you're watching live

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:46.030
and you'd like to put a
question in, please feel free,

00:00:46.030 --> 00:00:48.290
and we'll make time for those.

00:00:48.290 --> 00:00:49.742
Thanks.

00:00:49.742 --> 00:00:53.214
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:56.770
KELSEY CROWE: Hi,
good afternoon.

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.770
It's really good to
be here with you all.

00:00:59.770 --> 00:01:02.650
I live in San Francisco,
Bernal Heights neighborhood,

00:01:02.650 --> 00:01:06.100
which is a bedroom
community to Google,

00:01:06.100 --> 00:01:09.850
and it's actually been with
the help of a lot of Googlers

00:01:09.850 --> 00:01:11.440
that Help Each Other
Out got started,

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:13.090
whether attending
our launch event,

00:01:13.090 --> 00:01:15.610
or donating to our
Indiegogo campaign,

00:01:15.610 --> 00:01:17.620
participating in workshops.

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:22.630
So to be here in your company,
literally and figuratively,

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:24.350
is just a real treat.

00:01:24.350 --> 00:01:28.480
And Karen and I did
connect when her mom was

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:32.680
dying and since then, and
we have a friendship now.

00:01:32.680 --> 00:01:37.600
And I think that that
speaks to the bounty

00:01:37.600 --> 00:01:41.170
of learning how to connect
in times of vulnerability.

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:43.380
When we might want
to run away, there

00:01:43.380 --> 00:01:46.780
are some true benefits when
we actually do connect,

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:50.590
and that's what we're
here to talk about.

00:01:50.590 --> 00:01:55.409
My talk will focus mostly on
the notion of trust, that when

00:01:55.409 --> 00:01:56.950
being there with
others in their time

00:01:56.950 --> 00:02:01.290
of suffering, how can
we trust ourselves.

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:02.770
And then Karen and
I will be going

00:02:02.770 --> 00:02:04.750
into some Q&amp;A with
some practical tips

00:02:04.750 --> 00:02:07.240
too, around communication,
because we all want

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:08.449
to stay out of the dog house.

00:02:12.040 --> 00:02:14.650
So I don't know how
many of you here

00:02:14.650 --> 00:02:17.380
know somebody who might have
asked you, why the heck would

00:02:17.380 --> 00:02:19.090
you take some time
out of your day

00:02:19.090 --> 00:02:22.180
to hear a talk about suffering?

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:23.650
Because I doubt
you're a masochist.

00:02:26.320 --> 00:02:28.810
I do suspect,
however, that you may

00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:33.290
have had some brush
with suffering,

00:02:33.290 --> 00:02:36.590
enough to know that what we're
really here to talk about

00:02:36.590 --> 00:02:39.460
is meaning.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:42.530
Meaning comes from
work and relationships.

00:02:42.530 --> 00:02:47.770
And the relationships
that matter in our lives--

00:02:47.770 --> 00:02:51.610
the ones that sustain us through
the emotional ups and downs,

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:57.360
the depression, the breakups,
the professional screwups,

00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:59.440
the losses--

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:02.750
these relationships are
ones we don't make them

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:05.620
when we're on top of the world.

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:09.300
We forge them when
we're at our bottom.

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:10.790
And I hate to tell
you this guys,

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:13.800
but when you hit
your 40s, oh my god,

00:03:13.800 --> 00:03:15.480
everybody's hitting
some kind of bottom.

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:16.410
[AUDIENCE MURMURS]

00:03:16.410 --> 00:03:18.949
And then the bottom is falling
out from under the bottom.

00:03:18.949 --> 00:03:20.990
So I'm glad you're getting
started on this young.

00:03:24.760 --> 00:03:27.360
I founded Help Each Other
Out to make it easier

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:30.510
for us to build these
relationships, because as

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:34.030
important as they are,
it can be hard to do.

00:03:34.030 --> 00:03:36.090
So we offer empathy
boot camp workshops,

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:39.210
which I developed with
the help of people

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:42.760
in medicine, and in
business, and in therapy.

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:44.430
And we also do
public art exhibits

00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:48.390
on being there, which are these
neighborhood-wide installations

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:50.910
that we've done in several
San Francisco neighborhoods

00:03:50.910 --> 00:03:54.000
and in New York that feature
kind gestures that got people

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.370
through a difficult time.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:57.744
And then there is the book--

00:03:57.744 --> 00:03:59.160
"There Is No Good
Card for This"--

00:03:59.160 --> 00:04:00.534
that I wrote with
Emily McDowell,

00:04:00.534 --> 00:04:02.970
who is a wonderful
writer and illustrator.

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:05.370
And that book is based
on a lot of research

00:04:05.370 --> 00:04:07.890
that I did in this area.

00:04:07.890 --> 00:04:10.650
This is a lot of work
to do, to figure out

00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:13.350
if I should leave my
bereaved colleague

00:04:13.350 --> 00:04:16.620
a donut on their desk.

00:04:16.620 --> 00:04:18.690
Why do I do it?

00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:21.610
And I have two answers to that.

00:04:21.610 --> 00:04:24.330
The first is because
I'm actually not

00:04:24.330 --> 00:04:26.440
by nature very good at this.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:29.400
There are some people who just
seem really comfortable being

00:04:29.400 --> 00:04:31.680
around people's pain,
having emotionally

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:34.170
vulnerable conversations.

00:04:34.170 --> 00:04:36.810
That wasn't me.

00:04:36.810 --> 00:04:40.470
I am a Sagittarius
from Brooklyn.

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:41.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:41.910 --> 00:04:44.130
Anybody who knows
our species knows

00:04:44.130 --> 00:04:48.120
we are not the most empathic
creatures on the planet.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:50.820
We're far more quick to tell you
what we think about something

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:54.010
than we are to listen to
somebody else's perspective,

00:04:54.010 --> 00:04:56.820
and that can make for really
lively dinner conversation.

00:04:56.820 --> 00:05:00.270
It could make for a really
engaging team meeting,

00:05:00.270 --> 00:05:02.010
but it really doesn't
work when you're

00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:03.468
trying to connect
to somebody who's

00:05:03.468 --> 00:05:06.180
feeling emotionally vulnerable.

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:09.120
Time and time and time
again, I would let down

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:12.000
my friends who were going
through something hard--

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.030
a loss, a miscarriage,
a breakup.

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:17.520
I was that person
that would shy away,

00:05:17.520 --> 00:05:23.230
not because I didn't care, but
because like so many of us,

00:05:23.230 --> 00:05:26.260
when you don't know
what to do or say,

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:30.140
you might say nothing at all.

00:05:30.140 --> 00:05:32.804
I reached a wall
with this behavior

00:05:32.804 --> 00:05:34.220
when a friend from
graduate school

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:36.980
was diagnosed with
breast cancer.

00:05:36.980 --> 00:05:41.170
I don't know why I reached
that wall then, but I did.

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:44.300
And I recognized that
my reticence was not

00:05:44.300 --> 00:05:46.100
a gift to her.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:50.117
I wasn't sparing
her my awkwardness.

00:05:50.117 --> 00:05:51.200
I was just being a coward.

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:56.720
I wanted to be more responsible.

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:01.756
I wanted to align my caring
intentions with my actions,

00:06:01.756 --> 00:06:05.240
but I did not know how.

00:06:05.240 --> 00:06:07.940
I never did reach
out to my friend,

00:06:07.940 --> 00:06:11.660
but I did do what any
good social science

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:13.310
researcher would do.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:16.160
I researched the problem.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:19.252
I developed an online survey
of open-ended questions

00:06:19.252 --> 00:06:21.710
that basically asked what worked
and what didn't to get you

00:06:21.710 --> 00:06:23.280
through your difficult time.

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:24.350
That got legs.

00:06:24.350 --> 00:06:26.660
I got 900 responses,
supplemented that

00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:29.870
with a bunch of interviews, and
that's the basis of this book.

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:35.810
But still, it's a
lot to do, right,

00:06:35.810 --> 00:06:38.790
to just figure out how to be
there in times of suffering.

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:41.030
Why did it matter to me so much?

00:06:41.030 --> 00:06:45.500
Because I am sure if I were to
ask for hands, every one of you

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:49.490
have had that moment of
regret for saying something

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:55.400
that just landed wrong or for
not saying anything at all.

00:06:55.400 --> 00:06:58.220
But you move on.

00:06:58.220 --> 00:07:03.050
I couldn't move on, and that
leads to the second, deeper

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:05.870
reason that I started this work.

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:07.990
You see, my failure
to connect with people

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:10.850
in their times of
vulnerability was not because I

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:12.660
didn't know suffering.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:14.420
I wasn't green to grief.

00:07:14.420 --> 00:07:18.250
I did know suffering.

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:20.260
It didn't equip me
to know what to do,

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:23.350
but it did teach
me that it matters.

00:07:23.350 --> 00:07:26.440
So my story around that is this.

00:07:26.440 --> 00:07:28.830
I grew up knowing only my mom.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:31.030
I didn't know my dad.

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:34.150
I had no aunts, no uncles.

00:07:34.150 --> 00:07:37.200
My grandparents had passed
away a long time ago.

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:42.580
It was just she and I, and
we were really, really close.

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:47.860
She also had schizophrenia,
and she managed that illness

00:07:47.860 --> 00:07:51.220
until she no longer could.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:53.710
When I was 19,
she stopped taking

00:07:53.710 --> 00:07:56.800
her psychotropic medication.

00:07:56.800 --> 00:08:00.550
When I was 23, her
paranoia got so

00:08:00.550 --> 00:08:05.807
consuming that she changed
her number, changed the locks,

00:08:05.807 --> 00:08:07.390
and put out a
restraining order on me.

00:08:10.400 --> 00:08:13.790
There were some very
humiliating attempts

00:08:13.790 --> 00:08:17.160
to try to connect with her
again, but I never did.

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:18.130
And she did pass away.

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:26.660
That loss, that
loss of the mind,

00:08:26.660 --> 00:08:28.160
has no ritual for mourning.

00:08:30.700 --> 00:08:33.250
At that young age,
people weren't

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:34.480
thinking about what to do.

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:38.780
They were focused on their
careers and their friends.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:43.700
Save for a handful of
people, the loss of my small

00:08:43.700 --> 00:08:46.400
but entire family
went unmentioned.

00:08:50.050 --> 00:08:55.320
In response to that, of course,
I had some needs to belong,

00:08:55.320 --> 00:09:00.060
and they would really creep up
at the time of the holidays.

00:09:00.060 --> 00:09:02.640
Where was I going to eat?

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.060
When I had an overnight
stay in the hospital,

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:08.710
who was going to pick
me up the next day?

00:09:08.710 --> 00:09:12.420
When I went to the Peace Corps
for three years in Africa,

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:14.160
where was I going home to?

00:09:17.520 --> 00:09:21.030
Did I ever express these needs?

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:23.520
No.

00:09:23.520 --> 00:09:27.540
Because far more keenly
than that desire to belong

00:09:27.540 --> 00:09:33.000
was feeling shame for
having any needs at all.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.616
And I know I'm
not alone in this.

00:09:35.616 --> 00:09:38.040
In my workshops, I
ask people, what's

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:41.170
hard about asking for help?

00:09:41.170 --> 00:09:46.800
Responses they give me,
verbatim, are like these--

00:09:46.800 --> 00:09:51.130
fear of being a
burden, feeling like I

00:09:51.130 --> 00:09:54.910
should be able to
tolerate the situation,

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:58.770
fear that I will be seen
only for my affliction

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:04.980
and not as me, and the kicker,
always throughout, shame.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:11.780
It's this person-- this
person who's at the bottom

00:10:11.780 --> 00:10:13.730
of their well--

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:18.440
maybe we reach out and
offer them a self-help book,

00:10:18.440 --> 00:10:21.800
if we reach out at all.

00:10:21.800 --> 00:10:25.970
Maybe we ask them, let me know
if there's anything I can do.

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:30.680
I can guarantee you
most times they won't.

00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:35.950
And that self-help book, "How
You Can Manage Adversity,"

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:37.305
F you.

00:10:37.305 --> 00:10:39.245
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:43.060
What if we flipped the script?

00:10:43.060 --> 00:10:47.650
What if instead of buying
a book for that person,

00:10:47.650 --> 00:10:50.824
we bought something
like my book,

00:10:50.824 --> 00:10:53.860
a book about how we
can connect to others

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:56.440
in their time of pain?

00:10:56.440 --> 00:10:59.710
What if in the ways
that we prioritize

00:10:59.710 --> 00:11:04.180
our goals and our practices to
cultivate our emotional health

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:06.280
and our own physical health--

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:12.000
what if we applied that
to our relational health?

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.400
How much saner
would our world be?

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:17.130
How much more meaningful
would our lives become?

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:23.100
People who experience
pain very often

00:11:23.100 --> 00:11:29.490
experience a second kind of
pain of isolation, of shame.

00:11:32.580 --> 00:11:36.460
They're surrounded by care,
and they don't even know it.

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:41.560
I didn't want to be a part
of that problem anymore.

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:43.870
That is the second,
deeper reason why

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:47.080
I started Help Each Other Out.

00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:49.870
But even if we know that
it's really, really important

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:51.670
to connect in times
of difficulty,

00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:54.890
it can be super hard to do.

00:11:54.890 --> 00:11:58.210
I identify three
empathy roadblocks.

00:11:58.210 --> 00:12:02.680
One is fear of saying or
doing the wrong thing.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:06.480
We don't want to make
the situation worse.

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:11.750
Second, the time, the
emotional bandwidth-- our lives

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:13.129
are crazy.

00:12:13.129 --> 00:12:14.670
Our own lives could
be falling apart.

00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:18.030
It's so hard to see how you can
fit in somebody else's needs

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:20.610
into your schedule.

00:12:20.610 --> 00:12:23.760
And sometimes, it can seem that
when you acknowledge somebody's

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:28.260
needs, you've opened up a
Pandora's box of problems

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:30.810
that you then become responsible
for till the end of time.

00:12:33.576 --> 00:12:35.700
And then the third reason
that we may not reach out

00:12:35.700 --> 00:12:37.385
is because we don't want to pry.

00:12:37.385 --> 00:12:39.135
We don't want someone
to feel like they're

00:12:39.135 --> 00:12:41.190
a source of gossip.

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:45.150
We don't want to make
them uncomfortable.

00:12:45.150 --> 00:12:48.240
I have some really good news.

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:49.835
These fears are totally normal.

00:12:52.978 --> 00:12:55.770
The even better
news is that they're

00:12:55.770 --> 00:12:59.850
making it way too complicated.

00:12:59.850 --> 00:13:03.790
And I learned this from
my daughter, Georgia.

00:13:03.790 --> 00:13:06.180
She was five at the
time that she asked me

00:13:06.180 --> 00:13:07.430
from the backseat of our car--

00:13:07.430 --> 00:13:09.810
I'm driving over
the Bay Bridge--

00:13:09.810 --> 00:13:14.600
"Mom, what do you
do for a living?"

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:17.160
"Well," I said, "I
try to help friends

00:13:17.160 --> 00:13:19.730
be there for each other
when they're sad."

00:13:19.730 --> 00:13:23.010
"Oh," she said, "that's easy."

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:24.810
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:27.450
So she should not be in charge
of promotion for this book.

00:13:29.960 --> 00:13:30.510
"It is?"

00:13:30.510 --> 00:13:31.360
I said.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:34.440
"Well, what would you
say to help a friend?"

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:38.480
And she actually came up
with a pretty good list,

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:41.480
and I'm going to
share it with you.

00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:44.220
You gave some ideas of what
friends can do for each other

00:13:44.220 --> 00:13:45.030
when they're sad.

00:13:45.030 --> 00:13:47.830
GEORGIA: Friends
can say I'm sorry.

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:49.640
KELSEY CROWE: Mm-hmm.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:53.058
GEORGIA: Do you want
to play with me?

00:13:53.058 --> 00:13:55.036
Want to sit down with me?

00:13:55.036 --> 00:13:56.410
KELSEY CROWE
(VOICEOVER): Mm-hmm.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:14:03.577
GEORGIA: Also, do you
want to take a break?

00:14:03.577 --> 00:14:07.409
Do you want to
have a little hug?

00:14:11.589 --> 00:14:13.380
KELSEY CROWE: I'm seeing
some head nodding.

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:17.590
It works, right?

00:14:17.590 --> 00:14:20.430
It's not a bad list.

00:14:20.430 --> 00:14:22.150
So we're done.

00:14:22.150 --> 00:14:23.428
I think I can go home now.

00:14:23.428 --> 00:14:25.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:27.870
Beat the traffic.

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:31.660
It sounds so simple, doesn't it?

00:14:31.660 --> 00:14:36.180
But the saying goes,
simple is not always easy.

00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:40.110
Something happens between
then-- her age-- and now.

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:44.250
We enter into more domains
where we expect competence,

00:14:44.250 --> 00:14:47.580
productivity, fixing things.

00:14:47.580 --> 00:14:52.020
We've made mistakes, learned
not to trust ourselves.

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:54.480
By the time we're
adults, we become

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:57.930
so self-conscious about
how to just be there

00:14:57.930 --> 00:15:00.930
with somebody we care about.

00:15:00.930 --> 00:15:07.680
We imagine that there is some
Herculean gesture, some phrase,

00:15:07.680 --> 00:15:09.840
that could heal this
person's situation.

00:15:09.840 --> 00:15:13.522
It's just eluding me right
now, but when it comes to me,

00:15:13.522 --> 00:15:14.730
that's when I'll offer it up.

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:21.930
But the real news is there is
no perfect thing you can say,

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:23.790
there is no perfect
thing that you can

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:27.030
do, to fix someone's situation.

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:34.000
And honestly, that
perfect person,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.810
when your life is falling
apart, is the last person

00:15:37.810 --> 00:15:38.500
you want to see.

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:48.410
So let's unpack it a bit.

00:15:48.410 --> 00:15:51.060
What is behind connecting
in times of suffering?

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:53.480
What does it actually take?

00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:58.880
In my workshops, I have what
are called gesture cards.

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:02.570
They provide prompts that ask
people, what got you through?

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:06.020
And, what got you through with
a colleague, or a neighbor,

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:08.390
or a best friend,
or a family member?

00:16:08.390 --> 00:16:11.340
And I have hundreds and
hundreds and hundreds of these.

00:16:11.340 --> 00:16:13.790
So I'm going to
share some with you,

00:16:13.790 --> 00:16:16.790
and it's a highly representative
sample of what I see.

00:16:21.070 --> 00:16:24.190
What colleagues did
that touched me--

00:16:24.190 --> 00:16:25.990
"I had a miscarriage,
and my colleagues

00:16:25.990 --> 00:16:28.540
sent me a beautiful
bouquet of flowers

00:16:28.540 --> 00:16:33.070
with a lovely, heartfelt
message attached."

00:16:33.070 --> 00:16:35.220
A friend I hadn't
heard from in years--

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:43.140
"emailed/called to say 'I'm
sorry.'" Take note guys--

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:45.870
"my son came by and did all
the dishes and laundry."

00:16:51.180 --> 00:16:52.160
"Listened to me."

00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:59.680
"Brought me and my family meals
every night for over a month"--

00:16:59.680 --> 00:17:00.380
strangers.

00:17:04.099 --> 00:17:06.384
"My sister came to my house
after a terrible break

00:17:06.384 --> 00:17:08.990
up and made me something to eat.

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:11.504
She doesn't normally come over.

00:17:11.504 --> 00:17:12.170
It meant a lot."

00:17:15.190 --> 00:17:19.829
"Donated clothes when we
couldn't go home after 9/11."

00:17:19.829 --> 00:17:20.950
This was in New York City.

00:17:25.740 --> 00:17:29.760
How many of these gestures
require a significant grasp

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:31.198
of human psychology?

00:17:34.790 --> 00:17:38.610
How many of them
take a lot of time?

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:43.870
What's really amazing-- and this
surprised the heck out of me--

00:17:43.870 --> 00:17:46.530
is you don't even need to
have an intimate knowledge

00:17:46.530 --> 00:17:50.220
of a person's situation or
have a strong relationship

00:17:50.220 --> 00:17:51.885
with them.

00:17:51.885 --> 00:17:54.600
A couple of things that I
learned from these gesture

00:17:54.600 --> 00:17:57.600
cards and from my data--

00:17:57.600 --> 00:18:03.310
first, if you care,
your care belongs.

00:18:03.310 --> 00:18:05.460
So remember, when I
started this work,

00:18:05.460 --> 00:18:11.710
I had a matrix where you had the
gesture and the relationship.

00:18:11.710 --> 00:18:15.390
And I imagined that there
was the appropriate gesture

00:18:15.390 --> 00:18:17.170
for the appropriate
relationship,

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:20.610
and I was going to
unlock this science.

00:18:20.610 --> 00:18:23.070
Well, that was
completely foolhardy.

00:18:23.070 --> 00:18:25.500
Gestures from
colleagues and neighbors

00:18:25.500 --> 00:18:29.119
can be just as meaningful
and can look very much

00:18:29.119 --> 00:18:31.410
like the gesture that you
get from a friend or a family

00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:33.240
member.

00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:36.450
They can mean even more when
you don't have gestures coming

00:18:36.450 --> 00:18:39.640
from friends or family members.

00:18:39.640 --> 00:18:43.316
So if you care,
your care belongs.

00:18:43.316 --> 00:18:46.780
The second thing that I noticed
about the data and about

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:48.220
these gesture cards--

00:18:48.220 --> 00:18:52.330
people don't describe
appreciation for favors.

00:18:52.330 --> 00:18:55.180
They don't say, I asked
my brother to pick me up

00:18:55.180 --> 00:18:57.490
to go to chemo, and he did.

00:19:01.100 --> 00:19:06.040
A favor comes with some amount
of indebtedness, obligation.

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:09.960
We don't feel totally
thankful for that.

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:12.270
We are thankful for
unexpected offers.

00:19:15.216 --> 00:19:16.590
So that leads to
the second thing

00:19:16.590 --> 00:19:20.760
I noticed about this
data, which is reach out

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:22.230
and do not wait to be asked.

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:28.970
Let's say you're
ready to reach out.

00:19:28.970 --> 00:19:31.400
OK, you guys, you're ready.

00:19:31.400 --> 00:19:33.369
What do I do?

00:19:33.369 --> 00:19:34.910
If they don't tell
me what they need,

00:19:34.910 --> 00:19:37.980
how do I know how to respond?

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:40.980
I get this concern.

00:19:40.980 --> 00:19:42.830
And I would say
the answer in that

00:19:42.830 --> 00:19:47.380
lies in trust, to
trust yourself,

00:19:47.380 --> 00:19:49.920
and I have two tips for that.

00:19:49.920 --> 00:19:55.370
The first is to trust
what you know how to do.

00:19:55.370 --> 00:20:00.570
In fact, what you like to do.

00:20:00.570 --> 00:20:04.565
So for example, if you--

00:20:04.565 --> 00:20:07.850
I learned this the
hard way, actually,

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:10.850
as I learn too many things.

00:20:10.850 --> 00:20:15.107
I learned at some point that
people cook for somebody

00:20:15.107 --> 00:20:16.190
who's in a difficult time.

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:20.350
Maybe they're bereaved, they've
just had a baby, they're sick.

00:20:20.350 --> 00:20:22.640
Some people make dishes,
and they bring those over.

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:24.890
OK, that's what I'll do.

00:20:24.890 --> 00:20:28.560
Except I hate to cook.

00:20:28.560 --> 00:20:31.290
So when I would cook, it
would be with a lot of stress.

00:20:31.290 --> 00:20:33.770
I mean, it's like putting
out an all-point bulletin--

00:20:33.770 --> 00:20:35.780
I'm cooking.

00:20:35.780 --> 00:20:37.100
Handle me with kid gloves.

00:20:37.100 --> 00:20:38.990
I'm stressed.

00:20:38.990 --> 00:20:41.660
And I would go through
all of this work.

00:20:41.660 --> 00:20:44.480
I would often arrive
late and offer this dish

00:20:44.480 --> 00:20:47.840
with a ton of caveats
about why it tasted so bad.

00:20:51.080 --> 00:20:54.790
Nobody wants that dish.

00:20:54.790 --> 00:20:58.240
If, however, you
do like to cook,

00:20:58.240 --> 00:21:00.940
do not worry about the
other 20 casseroles that

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:04.510
are in the refrigerator,
because chances are 80% of them

00:21:04.510 --> 00:21:05.800
are from people like me.

00:21:05.800 --> 00:21:07.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:12.760
If you like to listen,
trust that just

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:16.150
by asking, "how are you today?"

00:21:16.150 --> 00:21:19.690
and really wanting
to know, that that

00:21:19.690 --> 00:21:22.360
is a very meaningful gesture.

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:25.300
Trust that if you
like getting donuts

00:21:25.300 --> 00:21:28.540
and you know your
colleague's favorite food,

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:31.000
bring them their favorite donut.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:36.610
Trust what you know how to do,
what you like to do, and just

00:21:36.610 --> 00:21:37.120
offer it.

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:43.570
The second tip for
building trust--

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:47.050
trust that is that bridge
between your intention

00:21:47.050 --> 00:21:48.380
and your action.

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:52.660
The second tip is to
trust what you know

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:56.230
and trust what you know deeply.

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:59.437
It can be very,
very intimidating

00:21:59.437 --> 00:22:01.270
when somebody is going
through an experience

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:04.120
that you haven't
gone through before.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:05.840
You may know
somebody, for example,

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:08.950
who's had a very significant
loss or a divorce,

00:22:08.950 --> 00:22:10.510
and you've never
been through that.

00:22:10.510 --> 00:22:14.140
So you doubt that
you have the capacity

00:22:14.140 --> 00:22:17.600
to connect with them
over this situation.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:21.130
But the reality is
no one has shared

00:22:21.130 --> 00:22:23.440
the exact same
experience with somebody

00:22:23.440 --> 00:22:27.820
else down to the
molecular level.

00:22:27.820 --> 00:22:32.740
And the other truth is
underlying suffering

00:22:32.740 --> 00:22:36.490
are just a few
components that actually

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:40.930
run across all kinds of
experiences with pain.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:44.260
So for example, if
you've never lost

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:47.710
somebody very,
very close to you,

00:22:47.710 --> 00:22:51.110
take a moment to look inside.

00:22:51.110 --> 00:22:57.700
You may know what it is
to feel lonely and lost.

00:22:57.700 --> 00:22:59.560
You may have never lost a job.

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:02.450
You may have never been fired.

00:23:02.450 --> 00:23:05.660
But take a moment
to look inside.

00:23:05.660 --> 00:23:09.050
You may know what it is to
have your confidence broken.

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:15.860
You may not be a member
of the widows' club,

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:19.380
but you are a member of the
frail and messy human club.

00:23:24.060 --> 00:23:27.600
So in conclusion,
I would say this.

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:34.130
When it comes to connecting
in times of difficulty, trust.

00:23:34.130 --> 00:23:38.000
Trust what you know how to do.

00:23:38.000 --> 00:23:41.740
Trust what you already know.

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:47.490
You can be rest
assured that even

00:23:47.490 --> 00:23:53.040
if your gesture or your phrase
was not needed at that time

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:58.370
that you offered it, that the
meaning and human connection,

00:23:58.370 --> 00:24:02.100
that kindness that
compelled you to try,

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:04.395
that most certainly was.

00:24:07.701 --> 00:24:08.200
Trust that.

00:24:12.628 --> 00:24:13.612
That's it.

00:24:13.612 --> 00:24:14.596
Thank you.

00:24:14.596 --> 00:24:18.040
