00:26:50.790 --> 00:26:53.636
AUDIENCE: The question I had--

00:26:53.636 --> 00:26:56.135
during the situation in what's
going on in Houston right now

00:26:56.135 --> 00:26:59.030
and in Florida, have
you seen some acts

00:26:59.030 --> 00:27:00.620
of kindness and
gratitude that really

00:27:00.620 --> 00:27:02.230
have stood out in your mind?

00:27:02.230 --> 00:27:05.030
KELSEY CROWE: Yes, well,
I think everyone in Texas

00:27:05.030 --> 00:27:11.870
is talking about how disaster
is bringing us back to humanity,

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:15.350
and the normal categories
of political party or what

00:27:15.350 --> 00:27:18.110
have you are really
starting to disappear.

00:27:18.110 --> 00:27:21.530
So seeing people
jump in and help,

00:27:21.530 --> 00:27:24.410
providing their time,
donating when you can,

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:31.100
which is actually a huge
source of help, it's ongoing.

00:27:31.100 --> 00:27:33.320
I mean, even in
my own community,

00:27:33.320 --> 00:27:37.760
people looking for housing
for people and lending a room.

00:27:37.760 --> 00:27:41.690
If you are at all amenable
to hosting, for example,

00:27:41.690 --> 00:27:44.600
and you have an extra room,
and you're in the area,

00:27:44.600 --> 00:27:46.490
to just make that available.

00:27:46.490 --> 00:27:49.630
It really, really counts.

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:51.770
AUDIENCE: First Dory
question-- how much variety

00:27:51.770 --> 00:27:54.380
is there in how different people
with different personalities

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:57.230
benefit from different
types of empathy?

00:27:57.230 --> 00:27:59.492
KELSEY CROWE: No, that's a
very analytical question,

00:27:59.492 --> 00:28:00.950
and that's kind of
where I started.

00:28:00.950 --> 00:28:02.650
[LAUGHS]

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:08.330
And the key-- what happens when
you begin with that question is

00:28:08.330 --> 00:28:11.060
then you get tripped up in
making this the right gesture

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:12.512
for the right person.

00:28:12.512 --> 00:28:13.970
And until you think
that it's going

00:28:13.970 --> 00:28:18.040
to lay out the way you
hope it's going to lay out,

00:28:18.040 --> 00:28:21.240
and until you figure that
out, you don't do anything.

00:28:21.240 --> 00:28:24.960
So I would recommend
stepping back and thinking,

00:28:24.960 --> 00:28:27.260
what do I actually like to do?

00:28:27.260 --> 00:28:30.560
So for example, I
like to buy flowers.

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:35.240
It's super cliche, but if I
can get some me time and put

00:28:35.240 --> 00:28:36.230
together a bouquet--

00:28:36.230 --> 00:28:39.620
which I wouldn't do for myself,
but I would very happily

00:28:39.620 --> 00:28:41.065
do that for somebody else--

00:28:41.065 --> 00:28:42.440
then that's what
I'm going to do.

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:46.560
And I no longer worry if this
person wanted flowers or not.

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:50.110
I just think about what
I was able to give.

00:28:50.110 --> 00:28:56.570
And some of that then also
is the flip side of giving,

00:28:56.570 --> 00:28:59.840
which is being able to receive.

00:28:59.840 --> 00:29:03.120
It's a pretty ungracious
person who says, well,

00:29:03.120 --> 00:29:05.090
I don't like daisies.

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:06.335
Why did they give me daisies?

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:10.970
So that's not on you.

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:14.520
If you make a gesture
that you know how to give,

00:29:14.520 --> 00:29:16.400
then just offer it up.

00:29:16.400 --> 00:29:19.550
If you like music, put
together a playlist

00:29:19.550 --> 00:29:21.290
of your favorite songs.

00:29:21.290 --> 00:29:24.440
Maybe this person never
expressed an interest in music.

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:27.940
Knowing that you gave
something that gives you joy

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:32.000
is so much better to receive
than receiving something

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:33.830
that someone has
a feeling caused

00:29:33.830 --> 00:29:38.630
you a lot of torture to do.

00:29:38.630 --> 00:29:40.790
That's really, really
where I would start and not

00:29:40.790 --> 00:29:45.271
even worry too much about
somebody else's personality

00:29:45.271 --> 00:29:45.770
type.

00:29:48.960 --> 00:29:51.570
AUDIENCE: Is there different
advice based upon the context,

00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:54.555
like compared to at work
or in personal life?

00:29:54.555 --> 00:29:57.180
Because I know there's different
barriers involved and whatnot.

00:29:57.180 --> 00:30:01.230
KELSEY CROWE: Yes, when
people come to my workshops,

00:30:01.230 --> 00:30:04.590
very often they're coming in
with the question about how

00:30:04.590 --> 00:30:07.170
to support a colleague.

00:30:07.170 --> 00:30:10.020
They wind up leaving
having the work infuse

00:30:10.020 --> 00:30:14.700
their entire social system
because it impacts everything.

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:17.370
But that question of what
to do for a colleague

00:30:17.370 --> 00:30:20.940
is particular vexing because
we have certain boundaries

00:30:20.940 --> 00:30:24.970
around professional,
private, public,

00:30:24.970 --> 00:30:27.870
and we want to honor
those for reasons

00:30:27.870 --> 00:30:33.840
of being respectful and
creating a healthy environment

00:30:33.840 --> 00:30:35.550
for accountability.

00:30:35.550 --> 00:30:38.370
So there's a lot of reasons
why we don't dive too deeply

00:30:38.370 --> 00:30:40.740
into somebody's personal life.

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:45.330
That all said, increasingly
over the generations,

00:30:45.330 --> 00:30:48.180
we are becoming
more public, and I

00:30:48.180 --> 00:30:50.730
think this is such a
good thing when we're

00:30:50.730 --> 00:30:53.430
going through something
difficult. More and more,

00:30:53.430 --> 00:30:55.740
people are just
aware that something

00:30:55.740 --> 00:30:57.330
is happening to your colleague.

00:30:57.330 --> 00:30:59.700
It's not a big secret.

00:30:59.700 --> 00:31:03.330
And so what winds up seeming
like respectful distance

00:31:03.330 --> 00:31:07.200
when not doing something
can actually feel very cold

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.900
and callous.

00:31:09.900 --> 00:31:13.500
So I would recommend
in the work context

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:16.680
to still reach out if you care.

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:17.850
This is really important.

00:31:17.850 --> 00:31:21.450
This is not to give you some
to-do list or marching orders

00:31:21.450 --> 00:31:25.740
to start giving bouquets
to every single person that

00:31:25.740 --> 00:31:26.760
crosses your path.

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:28.920
But if there's a colleague
that you care about--

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:30.720
and you don't have
to be that close--

00:31:30.720 --> 00:31:32.130
you can send an email.

00:31:32.130 --> 00:31:34.110
You can write a card.

00:31:34.110 --> 00:31:37.410
One woman, she talked
about a colleague who

00:31:37.410 --> 00:31:41.250
she wasn't that close with,
and she had casually mentioned,

00:31:41.250 --> 00:31:44.970
tomorrow would have
been my due date.

00:31:44.970 --> 00:31:47.790
And that colleague left her a
bouquet of flowers on her desk

00:31:47.790 --> 00:31:50.690
the next day.

00:31:50.690 --> 00:31:52.190
So in the workplace,
often there are

00:31:52.190 --> 00:31:54.230
gestures that you can
do that don't require

00:31:54.230 --> 00:31:58.520
a lot of in-depth conversation,
but that show I notice,

00:31:58.520 --> 00:32:01.020
and I care.

00:32:01.020 --> 00:32:04.290
By the same token, if you
actually do have a number

00:32:04.290 --> 00:32:07.850
of conversations-- you complain
about management together,

00:32:07.850 --> 00:32:12.300
you talk about the sports, or
Project Runway, or whatever--

00:32:12.300 --> 00:32:16.140
it's OK when you have a
private moment or to even nab

00:32:16.140 --> 00:32:20.250
someone in the hallway and say,
hey, I just want to check in.

00:32:20.250 --> 00:32:21.990
I just want to know
how you're doing.

00:32:21.990 --> 00:32:23.952
How are you doing today?

00:32:23.952 --> 00:32:25.410
That person will
say, oh, I'm fine.

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:26.696
I'm fine.

00:32:26.696 --> 00:32:29.380
And you say, OK.

00:32:29.380 --> 00:32:30.370
I just want to know.

00:32:30.370 --> 00:32:34.480
I mean, I'm here if
you want to tell me.

00:32:34.480 --> 00:32:37.110
And then that person may offer
a more authentic response,

00:32:37.110 --> 00:32:39.750
or they may say, nope, I'm OK.

00:32:39.750 --> 00:32:42.250
They're likely not going to go
home to their spouse and say,

00:32:42.250 --> 00:32:44.400
I can't believe that she
asked me how I was doing.

00:32:44.400 --> 00:32:47.220
It was so obnoxious.

00:32:47.220 --> 00:32:49.620
What I can guarantee you
is if nobody reaches out

00:32:49.620 --> 00:32:52.020
at the office, they are
going to be going home

00:32:52.020 --> 00:32:52.840
talking about that.

00:32:56.160 --> 00:32:57.660
AUDIENCE: When you
started your talk

00:32:57.660 --> 00:33:00.590
about what you went through
with your mother and everything,

00:33:00.590 --> 00:33:03.240
and you mentioned
shame, what were

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:05.860
some strategies you used to
neutralize the shame that you

00:33:05.860 --> 00:33:07.200
felt?

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:10.500
KELSEY CROWE: I'm not
a good shame overcomer.

00:33:10.500 --> 00:33:14.670
So if I write a book
about resilience,

00:33:14.670 --> 00:33:16.230
it would be about
how hard it is.

00:33:19.920 --> 00:33:22.800
I know the research behind
shame says you just have

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:24.870
to face your issue head-on.

00:33:24.870 --> 00:33:27.690
And certainly by
my doing this work,

00:33:27.690 --> 00:33:30.750
I have lost a lot
of shame, and that

00:33:30.750 --> 00:33:35.220
comes from engaging deeply
in the source of what

00:33:35.220 --> 00:33:38.880
I experienced, dialoguing
with others, even

00:33:38.880 --> 00:33:42.660
people who I thought weren't
there for me so much,

00:33:42.660 --> 00:33:46.830
having some of those
difficult conversations.

00:33:46.830 --> 00:33:48.630
That helped me to
get over the shame.

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:50.130
But now I have other
kinds of shame.

00:33:53.290 --> 00:33:55.530
AUDIENCE: Another
Dory question--

00:33:55.530 --> 00:33:58.230
when I'm trying to support
a friend, oftentimes

00:33:58.230 --> 00:34:01.200
one of the first things I
do is ask, how can I help?

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:03.870
When I started asking this, I
was sure this would be helpful,

00:34:03.870 --> 00:34:07.650
but 90% of the time, the answer
is something like, nothing.

00:34:07.650 --> 00:34:09.719
Is there any better
way you would recommend

00:34:09.719 --> 00:34:11.392
to discern their needs?

00:34:11.392 --> 00:34:12.600
KELSEY CROWE: Am I surprised?

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:14.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:17.243
The best way to handle
this situation--

00:34:17.243 --> 00:34:18.659
if you know that
a friend is going

00:34:18.659 --> 00:34:22.080
through something difficult,
just offer something.

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:25.380
So for example, hey, I want
to come by next Tuesday

00:34:25.380 --> 00:34:26.100
with pizza.

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:28.515
My only question is, is
it pepperoni or cheese?

00:34:31.050 --> 00:34:33.480
You just offer it.

00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:36.840
Make it very easy to accept by
saying, I'm going to the store.

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:38.400
I'm going to go get some things.

00:34:38.400 --> 00:34:40.290
Do you need anything?

00:34:40.290 --> 00:34:45.179
Or, if you love music like I've
said, put together a playlist.

00:34:45.179 --> 00:34:46.110
Just do it.

00:34:46.110 --> 00:34:47.310
Just offer it.

00:34:47.310 --> 00:34:49.719
Maybe that person wasn't
saying, god, I really,

00:34:49.719 --> 00:34:52.800
really hope somebody
sends me a playlist today.

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:54.790
That's not going to happen.

00:34:54.790 --> 00:34:58.200
But they're going to appreciate
your offer, your kindness

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:00.570
that's backed by
action, and they

00:35:00.570 --> 00:35:04.890
will be more receptive to asking
you for help in the future.

00:35:04.890 --> 00:35:08.020
But just saying, how can I help?

00:35:08.020 --> 00:35:09.990
It's a very hard
question for somebody

00:35:09.990 --> 00:35:13.990
who's suffering to hear and
respond to for a few reasons.

00:35:13.990 --> 00:35:15.940
First, because of the shame.

00:35:15.940 --> 00:35:17.790
Second, you often
don't quite know

00:35:17.790 --> 00:35:22.020
what you need when you're in
a moment of crisis or grief.

00:35:22.020 --> 00:35:25.110
You can't say, what I
really need today is

00:35:25.110 --> 00:35:29.340
somebody to ask me, how am I?

00:35:29.340 --> 00:35:32.400
What I really need
today is somebody--

00:35:32.400 --> 00:35:34.185
well, I do I do this--
to do my laundry.

00:35:34.185 --> 00:35:36.240
[LAUGHS]

00:35:37.110 --> 00:35:41.640
But very often, if you're in the
initial aftermath of a crisis,

00:35:41.640 --> 00:35:44.160
so much around you
is falling apart--

00:35:44.160 --> 00:35:48.300
the garden, the trash,
the dishes, keeping up

00:35:48.300 --> 00:35:53.790
with the bills, getting the
kid to daycare, let alone all

00:35:53.790 --> 00:35:56.520
the depression and the sadness--

00:35:56.520 --> 00:35:59.340
you could name a thousand
different things that you need

00:35:59.340 --> 00:36:02.470
and not find one for a response.

00:36:02.470 --> 00:36:03.930
So just offer up that--

00:36:03.930 --> 00:36:06.915
what you know how to do.

00:36:06.915 --> 00:36:09.690
AUDIENCE: Now, do you
think the issues we

00:36:09.690 --> 00:36:11.910
have here in this country
regarding reaching out

00:36:11.910 --> 00:36:13.500
to people, asking
if they need help

00:36:13.500 --> 00:36:17.029
is due to a cultural aspect
or is there something

00:36:17.029 --> 00:36:17.820
else deeply rooted?

00:36:17.820 --> 00:36:20.880
Because I've noticed that when
I've gone to other developing

00:36:20.880 --> 00:36:24.620
countries, the cultural bonds
seem to be much stronger,

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:27.240
and people seem to be more
open about their personal lives

00:36:27.240 --> 00:36:27.800
and whatnot.

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.250
KELSEY CROWE: Mm-hmm, yes.

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:30.430
It's very true.

00:36:30.430 --> 00:36:34.800
I mean, Americans have just
this history of pull yourself up

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:38.820
by your bootstraps
and the individualism,

00:36:38.820 --> 00:36:42.150
and it certainly, certainly
is reflected in our inability

00:36:42.150 --> 00:36:44.160
to ask for help.

00:36:44.160 --> 00:36:47.170
And I lived in Africa, and I've
also lived in South America

00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:48.000
and in Europe.

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.910
And it is certainly
true that we can

00:36:50.910 --> 00:36:54.540
be a lot more hesitant
to offer help and also,

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:57.084
frankly, to receive it.

00:36:57.084 --> 00:36:59.250
We're very, very likely
here to say, "oh, that's OK.

00:36:59.250 --> 00:37:04.480
I'm fine," because we feel
shame around receiving help.

00:37:04.480 --> 00:37:05.940
So there are differences.

00:37:09.606 --> 00:37:11.530
And even around
communication techniques

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:13.650
there can be some differences.

00:37:13.650 --> 00:37:17.610
The idea of giving
advice, it's not really

00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:20.510
recommended for people
in difficult times

00:37:20.510 --> 00:37:23.970
here who are American,
but advice giving

00:37:23.970 --> 00:37:25.610
can be seen a little
bit differently

00:37:25.610 --> 00:37:27.850
in some different cultures.

00:37:27.850 --> 00:37:33.120
AUDIENCE: My question is
around is there a not-do list?

00:37:33.120 --> 00:37:34.680
Did you ask that
before I came in?

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:35.610
KAREN MAY: No.

00:37:35.610 --> 00:37:37.800
We've talked about it.

00:37:37.800 --> 00:37:41.280
I'm smiling because we've
talked about the not-do list,

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:43.280
and it's also in the book.

00:37:43.280 --> 00:37:44.030
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:45.360
KAREN MAY: So great question.

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:46.440
KELSEY CROWE: Yes.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:48.030
And we all want
that not-do list.

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:49.361
[LAUGHS]

00:37:49.860 --> 00:37:53.244
So in the book,
Emily, my co-author,

00:37:53.244 --> 00:37:54.660
came up with a
great title for it,

00:37:54.660 --> 00:37:58.670
which was "Please Help
Me Not Be a Disaster."

00:37:58.670 --> 00:38:02.040
So the not-do list, I have a
couple of examples of those,

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:05.880
but I'm just going to say
what underlies pretty much

00:38:05.880 --> 00:38:11.580
every not-to-do is our tendency
to fix someone's problem.

00:38:11.580 --> 00:38:15.600
And again, Karen would
be the first to say,

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:19.442
we don't pay people at Google to
just sit around and be present.

00:38:19.442 --> 00:38:20.400
KAREN MAY: That's true.

00:38:20.400 --> 00:38:23.580
KELSEY CROWE: We are
paying you to fix things.

00:38:23.580 --> 00:38:25.620
And we feel a lot
of satisfaction

00:38:25.620 --> 00:38:27.280
when we can fix things.

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:33.960
So our culture of productivity,
problem-solving, it's awesome.

00:38:33.960 --> 00:38:38.220
Not around these times of
emotional vulnerability.

00:38:38.220 --> 00:38:44.280
Problem-solving, fixing, it
just shuts the whole thing down.

00:38:44.280 --> 00:38:46.950
Anybody have any
experience with this?

00:38:46.950 --> 00:38:50.800
And some examples of trying
to fix someone's problem--

00:38:50.800 --> 00:38:53.100
top on the list, giving advice.

00:38:55.810 --> 00:39:06.830
Someone tells you, oh, I just
can't get over feeling so sad.

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:09.620
I lost my dad two months
ago, and I'm still--

00:39:09.620 --> 00:39:11.610
I just think about
him every day.

00:39:14.360 --> 00:39:18.550
The response "have
you tried running?"

00:39:18.550 --> 00:39:20.080
is not helpful.

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:23.810
Or, "well, maybe if you
thought about--" not helpful.

00:39:23.810 --> 00:39:26.600
"You know what you should
do or what you could do--"

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:28.910
these are all signs that
you're giving advice.

00:39:28.910 --> 00:39:32.540
"Have you thought about--"
"you know what you could do--"

00:39:32.540 --> 00:39:39.220
"you know what you should do--"
instead, just say, "I'm sorry.

00:39:39.220 --> 00:39:42.310
I imagine that's really
hard," and be present.

00:39:42.310 --> 00:39:43.720
That's what's needed.

00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:46.270
So no fixing, no advice.

00:39:46.270 --> 00:39:49.060
And in the book I also then
talk about some non-listening

00:39:49.060 --> 00:39:51.550
styles, which are
a lot of don'ts.

00:39:51.550 --> 00:39:53.720
And everyone in this
room, including myself,

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:57.640
including Karen, we all have
our non-listening go-tos.

00:39:57.640 --> 00:40:01.910
It could, for example,
be the eternal optimist.

00:40:01.910 --> 00:40:06.490
So somebody who's always seeing
the bright side of a situation.

00:40:06.490 --> 00:40:11.560
It can be from, "oh god, I
ran out of gas on the bridge,

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:14.170
and I had to wait three
hours for a toll truck."

00:40:14.170 --> 00:40:18.340
"At least a toll truck
came," down to the deepest

00:40:18.340 --> 00:40:20.290
forms of suffering.

00:40:20.290 --> 00:40:25.390
Or somebody is told to
see a silver lining.

00:40:25.390 --> 00:40:29.620
Gratitude, sure, it's very, very
helpful for helping you cope.

00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:32.740
Finding meaning in tragedy,
it's been scientifically

00:40:32.740 --> 00:40:35.440
proven it helps us.

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:38.410
But that meaning that we
find, that gratitude that we

00:40:38.410 --> 00:40:42.460
experience, it can never
be handed from outside.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:45.230
It only gets
cultivated from within.

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:49.570
So never try to offer somebody
an optimistic perspective.

00:40:49.570 --> 00:40:53.710
I, as a non-listening
style, am a doomsayer.

00:40:53.710 --> 00:40:56.530
Someone may say
something really tragic,

00:40:56.530 --> 00:40:59.166
and I say, oh my
god, that's horrible!

00:40:59.166 --> 00:41:00.790
And then they wind
up responding to me,

00:41:00.790 --> 00:41:03.980
no, no, no, it's not that bad.

00:41:03.980 --> 00:41:06.670
And they wound up not feeling
like they can actually

00:41:06.670 --> 00:41:08.830
share what they're
feeling because then they

00:41:08.830 --> 00:41:10.090
feel they have to protect--

00:41:10.090 --> 00:41:12.280
deflect my alarm.

00:41:12.280 --> 00:41:14.740
So of course the doomsayer
hates the optimist.

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:18.180
And those two often marry
each other, so pay attention.

00:41:18.180 --> 00:41:19.911
[LAUGHTER]

00:41:20.410 --> 00:41:22.600
But so either reacting
with strong alarm

00:41:22.600 --> 00:41:28.120
to somebody's situation
or severe positivity

00:41:28.120 --> 00:41:31.990
can be really, really a don't,
as well as giving advice.

00:41:31.990 --> 00:41:34.450
I have several more
examples, but it all

00:41:34.450 --> 00:41:39.490
comes down to trying to
adjust how a person is viewing

00:41:39.490 --> 00:41:41.870
or handling their situation.

00:41:41.870 --> 00:41:45.460
And so often what winds up
happening when you do that with

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:50.440
any of those don'ts is you make
that person feel more ashamed,

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:52.900
as if they should be
having it together.

00:41:55.720 --> 00:42:01.240
Rarely is that our call to
make under normal grieving

00:42:01.240 --> 00:42:02.050
circumstances.

00:42:02.050 --> 00:42:04.030
Of course, there are
times when somebody

00:42:04.030 --> 00:42:06.670
is heading into a dangerous
zone, and that's different.

00:42:10.170 --> 00:42:11.170
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:42:11.170 --> 00:42:11.670
Oops.

00:42:11.670 --> 00:42:14.170
Is it on?

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:15.330
OK.

00:42:15.330 --> 00:42:18.470
I have a followup question to
that because I have a friend

00:42:18.470 --> 00:42:21.039
that I've been
supporting for years.

00:42:21.039 --> 00:42:22.705
KELSEY CROWE: Say
that again, I'm sorry.

00:42:22.705 --> 00:42:25.940
AUDIENCE: I have a
friend, and she's

00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:29.730
been having issues with her
family for many, many years.

00:42:29.730 --> 00:42:33.710
And I've been there to
support her, listen to her,

00:42:33.710 --> 00:42:36.590
and this has been going
on for maybe 10 years.

00:42:36.590 --> 00:42:39.410
And I'm at the point where I
really want to give advice.

00:42:39.410 --> 00:42:42.997
I try to give
advice, but she's not

00:42:42.997 --> 00:42:44.580
interested in listening
to the advice.

00:42:44.580 --> 00:42:47.570
But I can clearly see
that some of the issues

00:42:47.570 --> 00:42:49.730
that she's having
with her family is

00:42:49.730 --> 00:42:52.380
because of her actions
and her response.

00:42:52.380 --> 00:42:55.610
It's really not the
family that much.

00:42:55.610 --> 00:43:00.160
And I discovered
that, but when I

00:43:00.160 --> 00:43:03.110
try to tell her that she
might have a role in this,

00:43:03.110 --> 00:43:05.120
she just shuts me down.

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:08.150
So now I'm at the point I
don't know what to do anymore

00:43:08.150 --> 00:43:11.870
because I want to be there for
her, i want to support her,

00:43:11.870 --> 00:43:17.350
but I also want her to realize
that it takes two to tango.

00:43:17.350 --> 00:43:20.780
And I don't know
how to move forward.

00:43:20.780 --> 00:43:23.510
KELSEY CROWE: That's
a real, real problem,

00:43:23.510 --> 00:43:25.820
and I talk about
it in my book too.

00:43:25.820 --> 00:43:29.450
So there are problems
sometimes that consume us

00:43:29.450 --> 00:43:36.080
so much and for so long,
and the people around us

00:43:36.080 --> 00:43:38.780
who care about us don't
even feel like they

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:41.610
know who we are anymore.

00:43:41.610 --> 00:43:44.870
So as a friend who's
seeing somebody

00:43:44.870 --> 00:43:49.520
consumed by their problem
two, three, four years out,

00:43:49.520 --> 00:43:53.180
that's reached a whole other
threshold of difficulty.

00:43:53.180 --> 00:43:55.730
And the way to begin
that conversation

00:43:55.730 --> 00:43:57.440
is not with, advice
even though you

00:43:57.440 --> 00:44:02.330
see so many other avenues
this person could take,

00:44:02.330 --> 00:44:04.730
so many books they
should read, so many ways

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:07.910
to handle this situation--
it's so clear in front of you,

00:44:07.910 --> 00:44:08.910
and she's not seeing it.

00:44:08.910 --> 00:44:11.630
And you just want to do
a PowerPoint for her,

00:44:11.630 --> 00:44:13.850
walk her through it.

00:44:13.850 --> 00:44:16.970
It's not going to
work, as you know.

00:44:16.970 --> 00:44:19.280
The place to begin
in that conversation

00:44:19.280 --> 00:44:23.900
is not with advice, it's
where you are vulnerable,

00:44:23.900 --> 00:44:26.530
and that means talking about
your relationship to her.

00:44:29.400 --> 00:44:30.930
You've lost your
friend, I'm sure,

00:44:30.930 --> 00:44:35.620
on some level because she is
so caught up in this dialogue.

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:39.270
And you probably feel that you
can't talk on neutral ground

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:41.850
with things that are
going on for you.

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:45.280
It's hard to trust
somebody who's

00:44:45.280 --> 00:44:49.130
so easily consumed
by this obsession

00:44:49.130 --> 00:44:53.030
and so easily
pulled apart by it.

00:44:53.030 --> 00:44:57.000
And so where it's vulnerable
for you is to say,

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:03.960
I have to say I can't hang
with where this is right now.

00:45:03.960 --> 00:45:06.190
I can't feel safe.

00:45:06.190 --> 00:45:09.720
I don't feel that I can
be around this problem

00:45:09.720 --> 00:45:13.570
that you have and not
because I don't love you.

00:45:13.570 --> 00:45:16.710
I've loved you for years,
but you are changing.

00:45:16.710 --> 00:45:18.240
Does that make sense?

00:45:18.240 --> 00:45:22.170
You are not the person
who I knew 10 years ago.

00:45:22.170 --> 00:45:24.060
Or if she is the
person and you've

00:45:24.060 --> 00:45:29.430
changed, where you no longer
want to just entertain

00:45:29.430 --> 00:45:33.240
stories of failure,
about people's failures,

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:36.330
then that's part of
the dialogue too.

00:45:36.330 --> 00:45:40.080
Always emphasizing that
you love and care for her,

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:42.660
but that you don't
know what to do

00:45:42.660 --> 00:45:45.240
with this problem, which
isn't that she's not

00:45:45.240 --> 00:45:47.200
taking your advice.

00:45:47.200 --> 00:45:51.050
The problem is that you aren't
connecting with her anymore.

00:45:51.050 --> 00:45:52.410
Does that makes sense?

00:45:52.410 --> 00:45:55.110
That's a far more
vulnerable place

00:45:55.110 --> 00:45:58.080
to be in the conversation
than offering advice,

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:01.960
but it's the only way that
she's going to change.

00:46:01.960 --> 00:46:05.970
When people realize that their
obsessions with their problems

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:10.190
are having consequences
on their relationships,

00:46:10.190 --> 00:46:15.240
then it's in their hands to
make some choices around it.

00:46:15.240 --> 00:46:17.090
Does that help?

00:46:17.090 --> 00:46:18.890
AUDIENCE: Kind of,
but it also opens up

00:46:18.890 --> 00:46:21.000
a lot of other questions.

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:22.430
How do I phrase that?

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:23.390
How do I word that?

00:46:23.390 --> 00:46:24.680
How do I even--

00:46:24.680 --> 00:46:25.440
yes, it's tough.

00:46:25.440 --> 00:46:28.094
KELSEY CROWE: I think you
can even say, first of all,

00:46:28.094 --> 00:46:29.760
I clearly care about
this because you've

00:46:29.760 --> 00:46:32.449
brought this up to me.

00:46:32.449 --> 00:46:33.740
I really care about this issue.

00:46:33.740 --> 00:46:35.750
I've been thinking about
how to deal with this.

00:46:35.750 --> 00:46:38.390
Just showing your
concern, just being you.

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:39.530
There is no perfect phrase.

00:46:39.530 --> 00:46:41.720
There's nothing perfect
that you can say or do.

00:46:41.720 --> 00:46:43.642
This conversation
is going to suck.

00:46:43.642 --> 00:46:45.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:46.852 --> 00:46:49.310
Just show how much you care
and all the thought that you've

00:46:49.310 --> 00:46:51.768
been putting up into this moment
of talking to her and say,

00:46:51.768 --> 00:46:54.200
"and I don't know how to
make this conversation

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:57.790
happen going forward, but
this is what I'm feeling.

00:46:57.790 --> 00:47:01.130
I want you to know I don't want
to be the friend that runs away

00:47:01.130 --> 00:47:08.270
from you, and I want to
feel more connected to you.

00:47:08.270 --> 00:47:11.120
And I need some more
positivity from you,"

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:14.040
or whatever it is, whatever
the particularities are.

00:47:14.040 --> 00:47:17.360
It is going to be a hard,
difficult conversation,

00:47:17.360 --> 00:47:21.380
and that really gets
around authenticity.

00:47:21.380 --> 00:47:26.100
And some of our friendships
are more authentic than others.

00:47:26.100 --> 00:47:29.780
And it's you doing your own
inventory-- how authentic do

00:47:29.780 --> 00:47:32.240
I want this relationship to be?

00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:35.300
And you may decide, I don't
want it to be that authentic,

00:47:35.300 --> 00:47:37.562
but then you do not
open yourself up

00:47:37.562 --> 00:47:39.020
for hearing all of
these complaints

00:47:39.020 --> 00:47:41.410
because that's only a
drain on your energy.

00:47:41.410 --> 00:47:42.580
Does that make sense?

00:47:45.371 --> 00:47:47.120
AUDIENCE: I just wanted
to ask when you're

00:47:47.120 --> 00:47:50.810
speaking to a friend, a
friend in that situation,

00:47:50.810 --> 00:47:54.380
and can brainstorm
action items that they

00:47:54.380 --> 00:47:58.280
want to do, how do you hold them
accountable in a way that's not

00:47:58.280 --> 00:48:03.800
really all in their
face, but you just

00:48:03.800 --> 00:48:08.510
want them to do what
they say they'll do?

00:48:08.510 --> 00:48:11.830
KELSEY CROWE: You tell
them to hire a coach.

00:48:11.830 --> 00:48:13.340
AUDIENCE: OK, so
how do you do that?

00:48:13.340 --> 00:48:16.340
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:16.340 --> 00:48:19.610
For instance, I have
a friend who admits,

00:48:19.610 --> 00:48:21.440
I have a lot going
on, and I think

00:48:21.440 --> 00:48:26.600
it's more than my friends can
handle or my family can handle.

00:48:26.600 --> 00:48:28.310
And I think I should
talk to someone.

00:48:28.310 --> 00:48:30.370
But then it won't happen.

00:48:30.370 --> 00:48:32.560
It hasn't happened, forever.

00:48:32.560 --> 00:48:36.050
And so how do you hold them
accountable for talking

00:48:36.050 --> 00:48:40.046
to someone, or getting a
coach, or whatever it is?

00:48:40.046 --> 00:48:42.170
KELSEY CROWE: I mean, the
thing about friendships--

00:48:42.170 --> 00:48:44.044
and that's where they
are different from work

00:48:44.044 --> 00:48:45.550
relationships--

00:48:45.550 --> 00:48:49.710
is we don't often hold each
other accountable for things.

00:48:49.710 --> 00:48:53.420
In fact, what you find bringing
is less accountability and more

00:48:53.420 --> 00:48:58.070
patience, so having patience
for your friend that is just

00:48:58.070 --> 00:49:00.320
struggling with moving on.

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:03.830
If it's not deriding from the
quality of your relationship--

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:05.270
does this make sense?

00:49:05.270 --> 00:49:07.460
If in fact you have
a great relationship,

00:49:07.460 --> 00:49:10.250
your friend just
has this one area

00:49:10.250 --> 00:49:18.050
where they want to improve,
meet certain milestones,

00:49:18.050 --> 00:49:23.210
listen to them, be disappointed
that they failed themselves.

00:49:23.210 --> 00:49:24.950
But you are not, as
a friend, the person

00:49:24.950 --> 00:49:27.140
to hold them
accountable for that.

00:49:27.140 --> 00:49:29.060
Where you can hold
someone accountable

00:49:29.060 --> 00:49:32.420
is if they're behaving
in a way that's affecting

00:49:32.420 --> 00:49:34.540
your relationship to them.

00:49:34.540 --> 00:49:40.940
And that, if you don't
see improvement over time,

00:49:40.940 --> 00:49:43.700
that's on them.

00:49:43.700 --> 00:49:47.120
It is never our job
as friends to expect

00:49:47.120 --> 00:49:51.720
to keep people accountable
for how they behave.

00:49:51.720 --> 00:49:54.780
And so sometimes in
both of these cases,

00:49:54.780 --> 00:49:59.520
you just reach your own
reckoning around that.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:02.870
Something that you
learn as you get older

00:50:02.870 --> 00:50:06.650
is the value of
patience, that no one

00:50:06.650 --> 00:50:10.760
does everything they
say they're going to do,

00:50:10.760 --> 00:50:13.430
and then also secondly,
the value of our time

00:50:13.430 --> 00:50:19.780
and energy in that we can't
invest our heart into everybody

00:50:19.780 --> 00:50:22.970
that we thought we could.

00:50:22.970 --> 00:50:25.070
So figuring out that balance.

00:50:25.070 --> 00:50:27.570
KAREN MAY: It looks like we
have time for one more question.

00:50:27.570 --> 00:50:29.420
Jordan, I'll ask if there's
something on the Dory

00:50:29.420 --> 00:50:30.336
that you want to read.

00:50:30.336 --> 00:50:31.640
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:50:31.640 --> 00:50:33.620
It can be just as difficult
to ask for support

00:50:33.620 --> 00:50:34.940
as it can be to give it.

00:50:34.940 --> 00:50:36.410
Do you have any
thoughts on asking

00:50:36.410 --> 00:50:38.807
for help in difficult times?

00:50:38.807 --> 00:50:41.390
KELSEY CROWE: Anyone who's even
thinking about asking for help

00:50:41.390 --> 00:50:44.360
is in such a good place,
so kudos to whoever

00:50:44.360 --> 00:50:46.300
asked that question.

00:50:46.300 --> 00:50:48.020
It's great.

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:50.990
I think you want to
ask people for help

00:50:50.990 --> 00:50:53.720
in areas where they're strong.

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:57.690
So if your friend is
always late, for example--

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:00.950
and we all know that person--

00:51:00.950 --> 00:51:05.542
do not ask them to drive
you to court, to drive you

00:51:05.542 --> 00:51:06.500
to your chemo session--

00:51:06.500 --> 00:51:07.880
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:07.880 --> 00:51:15.140
--to meet with your doctor, none
of the life-altering matters.

00:51:15.140 --> 00:51:17.360
Don't put them
under that pressure.

00:51:17.360 --> 00:51:19.760
But if, in fact, they're
a really great listener--

00:51:19.760 --> 00:51:23.960
it's not uncommon for that open
kind of person who's fluid with

00:51:23.960 --> 00:51:27.910
time is also good in
the emotional realm--

00:51:27.910 --> 00:51:31.730
say, can you just
come over tonight?

00:51:31.730 --> 00:51:33.680
I just need some company.

00:51:33.680 --> 00:51:37.580
Or you have a friend who's
pretty light and bubbly who

00:51:37.580 --> 00:51:40.490
may not be very comfortable
with awkward, emotionally

00:51:40.490 --> 00:51:46.850
fraught conversations, but is
really good for just escapism.

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:49.050
Say, would you watch
reality TV with me?

00:51:49.050 --> 00:51:50.280
Let's go to a movie.

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:54.470
Play to people's strengths,
as aware of them as you are,

00:51:54.470 --> 00:51:56.120
so that you give
them an opportunity

00:51:56.120 --> 00:52:00.080
to give what they
know how to give.

00:52:00.080 --> 00:52:01.730
And don't ask them
to give something

00:52:01.730 --> 00:52:03.170
that's really hard to give.

00:52:07.862 --> 00:52:08.570
KAREN MAY: Great.

00:52:08.570 --> 00:52:10.970
Well, terrific questions
and great advice

00:52:10.970 --> 00:52:12.860
to all of us to think about--

00:52:12.860 --> 00:52:15.560
what we have to give and
what others have to give us.

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:17.900
And thank you for
writing your book

00:52:17.900 --> 00:52:19.500
and for joining us here today.

00:52:19.500 --> 00:52:19.880
KELSEY CROWE: Thank you.

00:52:19.880 --> 00:52:20.340
KAREN MAY: Thank you.

00:52:20.340 --> 00:52:21.798
KELSEY CROWE: Thanks
for having me.

00:52:21.798 --> 00:52:24.550
[APPLAUSE]

